title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Assume the Galois group of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-0052.xml"
addr="gr-0052"
title="Solvable Group">solvable</fr:link>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-001S.xml"
addr="nt-001S"
title="Splitting Field of a Polynomial">splitting field</fr:link> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G=\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {L} / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex>, then there exists groups
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[1=G_{0}\mathrel {<} G_{1}\mathrel {<}…\mathrel {<} G_{n}=G]]></fr:tex>
such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G_{j}\mathrel {\trianglelefteq } G_{j+1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G_{j+1}/G_{j}]]></fr:tex> is cyclic.</fr:p>
<fr:p>By the Galois correspondence, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G_{n-i}]]></fr:tex> corresponds to Galois extensions <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{i}/\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}=L_{0}\subset  L_{1}\subset …\subset  L_{n}=\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G_{n-i}=\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (L_{n} / L_{i})]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (L_{i+1}/L_{i})\cong \frac {\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {L} /L_{i})}{\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {L} /L_{i+1})}=\frac {G_{n-i}}{G_{n-i-1}}]]></fr:tex>
is cyclic. <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-004F.xml"
addr="nt-004F"
title="Composite of root extensions is a root extension">Then we see</fr:link> each element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> lies in a <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-004D.xml"
addr="nt-004D"
title="Root Extension">Root Extension</fr:link>, hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is solvable by radicals.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is solvable by radicals. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> be a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> lying in a root extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-004F.xml"
addr="nt-004F"
title="Composite of root extensions is a root extension">Then we see</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> lies in a solvable Galois extension <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L} / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> is Galois, it must contain the splitting extension <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> is a quotient of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {L} / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> and therefore it is solvable.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 

 
   
